WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.270 --> 00:00:09.780
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:09.780 --> 00:00:15.330
This is a complete course for the CCNA, Cisco
Certified Network Associate.

00:00:15.330 --> 00:00:20.560
In this video we will look at an essential
part of the course – the labs in Cisco Packet

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:22.140
Tracer.

00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:24.300
First of all, what is a lab?

00:00:24.300 --> 00:00:30.590
In the world of IT, ‘doing labs’ or ‘labbing’
refers to hands-on practice with the technology

00:00:30.590 --> 00:00:32.250
you’re studying.

00:00:32.250 --> 00:00:37.380
Since you’re studying for the CCNA, labbing
means practicing configuring Cisco routers

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:39.710
and switches.

00:00:39.710 --> 00:00:43.440
There are a few options for CCNA labs.

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:48.920
One is to buy actual physical Cisco hardware,
real Cisco routers and switches.

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:53.560
However, that can be expensive and isn’t
very convenient.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:59.289
Fortunately Cisco has an amazing tool called
Packet Tracer which lets you set up simulated

00:00:59.289 --> 00:01:01.590
networks on your computer.

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:05.860
We will be using Packet Tracer for the labs
in this course.

00:01:05.860 --> 00:01:11.250
Packet Tracer is free, quick and easy to set
up, and lets you create simulated network

00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:15.150
labs without having to buy any hardware.

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:20.400
The network devices in packet tracer aren’t
real network devices, it’s just software

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:25.740
designed to simulate network devices so you
can practice configuring them.

00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:30.500
In this video we won’t actually configure
any routers and switches, since we haven’t

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:33.680
learned any configurations yet in the course.

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:38.070
Instead we’ll just get familiar with the
Packet Tracer user interface and how to build

00:01:38.070 --> 00:01:40.790
simple networks.

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:44.030
First of all, how can you download Cisco Packet
Tracer?

00:01:44.030 --> 00:01:47.510
You can download it for free from Cisco on
this page.

00:01:47.510 --> 00:01:52.430
Note that I have created a simple redirect
link that will take you to this page, it is

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:57.040
jitl.jp/packet-tracer.

00:01:57.040 --> 00:01:59.670
Follow that link and it will take you here.

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:03.439
However, first you will probably see this
login page.

00:02:03.439 --> 00:02:05.940
You need a Cisco account to download Packet
Tracer.

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:08.500
So, you can log in here.

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:13.110
Or if you don’t have an account yet, click
on Sign Up at the bottom of this page to create

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:14.950
one.

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:22.040
Once you have created an account and logged
in, my link jitl.jp/packet-tracer will allow

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:24.520
you to see this page.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:29.440
First let me point out that Cisco’s learning
platform Net Academy has a few courses about

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:31.780
how to use Packet Tracer.

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:36.310
If you really want to learn how to master
Packet Tracer itself, you can take these courses

00:02:36.310 --> 00:02:41.300
like ‘Getting Started with Cisco Packet
Tracer’, a short 2 hour course.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:46.150
Or the one below it, ‘Exploring Networking
with Cisco Packet Tracer’.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:50.670
In my course we won’t look at all of the
different functionalities of Packet Tracer,

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:53.390
just the ones we need to do the labs in my
course.

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:58.599
So, if you’re interested in learning more
about Packet Tracer you can take these free

00:02:58.599 --> 00:03:00.379
courses from Cisco.

00:03:00.379 --> 00:03:06.380
Anyway, scroll down and this is where you
can download Packet Tracer itself.

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:14.540
It is available for Windows in 64-bit and
32-bit versions, as well as Ubuntu and macOS.

00:03:14.540 --> 00:03:20.380
Download the appropriate version for your
computer, and install it like any other program.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:24.990
For my course, download the latest version,
which is 8.2 at the time I’m making this

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:26.530
video.

00:03:26.530 --> 00:03:30.549
If you have an old version, you might not
be able to run some of the labs.

00:03:30.549 --> 00:03:35.390
Old versions of Packet Tracer can’t open
lab files made in newer versions of Packet

00:03:35.390 --> 00:03:36.530
Tracer.

00:03:36.530 --> 00:03:42.049
However, new versions of Packet Tracer can
open lab files made in older versions of Packet

00:03:42.049 --> 00:03:43.049
Tracer.

00:03:43.049 --> 00:03:48.260
So, if you have the latest version you should
be able to open all of the lab files.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:52.049
Now, how can you get the lab files I provide
for my course?

00:03:52.049 --> 00:03:55.290
It’s the same as the Anki flashcards.

00:03:55.290 --> 00:04:00.189
If you got the link for the flashcards, the
lab files are in that same Google Drive so

00:04:00.189 --> 00:04:02.849
there’s no need to follow these steps again.

00:04:02.849 --> 00:04:06.120
But I’ll demonstrate once more just in case.

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:09.150
Here is the first lesson of the course again.

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:14.610
In the top line of the description there is
this link: Free CCNA flashcards and Packet

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:16.709
Tracer labs for the course.

00:04:16.709 --> 00:04:22.509
And the link is jitl.jp/ccna-files.

00:04:22.509 --> 00:04:29.630
Click on that link and you will be redirected
here, to sendfox.com/jeremysitlab.

00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:34.350
Enter your first name and email here and then
click join, and then you should get the files

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:35.940
in your email.

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:40.461
If there are any issues, for example if you
don’t get the emails for some reason, send

00:04:40.461 --> 00:04:47.600
me an email at info@jeremysitlab.com and I’ll
get back to you when I check my emails.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:51.630
However please wait at least 10 minutes before
you send me an email.

00:04:51.630 --> 00:04:54.900
Sometimes it takes a bit of time for the emails
to be sent.

00:04:54.900 --> 00:05:00.211
Okay, once you’ve got my lab files, open
the lab file labeled ‘Day 1 Lab’ in Packet

00:05:00.211 --> 00:05:03.590
Tracer and let’s get started.

00:05:03.590 --> 00:05:07.870
Note that, when you install Packet Tracer
and then open it, you will have to login to

00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:10.410
your Cisco account again.

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:14.490
After that, you should see my lab file like
this if you opened Packet Tracer by clicking

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:16.520
on the lab file.

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:22.020
If not, just go to the File menu and click
Open to open my lab file.

00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:27.630
In my lab files the lab instructions will
usually be on the left or bottom of the screen,

00:05:27.630 --> 00:05:31.660
and then there will be some devices I’ve
already placed in the network.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:36.230
In this first lab, there is just one router
which I have named ‘The Internet’.

00:05:36.230 --> 00:05:41.910
Then, the lab instructions tell us to place
the other devices to make a network.

00:05:41.910 --> 00:05:46.210
Note that, throughout the course I expect
that you will be using my pre-made lab files

00:05:46.210 --> 00:05:48.240
to do your labs.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:52.930
You are free to make the labs yourself from
scratch, without downloading my lab files,

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:55.630
but that won’t work for all of my labs.

00:05:55.630 --> 00:05:58.750
Some labs in the course require ‘troubleshooting’.

00:05:58.750 --> 00:06:03.710
In those labs I purposefully made some configuration
mistakes, so it’s your job to find those

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:05.580
mistakes and fix them.

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:10.720
Okay, before we go through the lab instructions
for this first lab I want to show you the

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:13.630
Packet Tracer preferences menu.

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:17.970
Go to Options in the top menu, and then Preferences.

00:06:17.970 --> 00:06:23.280
In this first tab, the Interface tab, you
can select things like whether or not Device

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:25.130
Model labels are shown.

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:32.360
I usually have this off, but if I turn it
on notice that above ‘The Internet’ 2911

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:33.360
appears.

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:39.419
That is the model name of this router, it’s
a Cisco 2911 router, I just named it ‘The

00:06:39.419 --> 00:06:41.620
Internet’ to represent the Internet.

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:46.789
I prefer to have device model labels off,
so I’ll remove this.

00:06:46.789 --> 00:06:51.849
If you don’t want to show the Device Name,
you could uncheck this here too, but I think

00:06:51.849 --> 00:06:53.699
it’s best to leave the names on.

00:06:53.699 --> 00:06:57.650
Anyway, feel free to check out some of these
other settings if you want.

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:02.379
I just want to point out one more tab, that
is the Font tab.

00:07:02.379 --> 00:07:08.190
Here you can change the font sizes in Packet
Tracer, for example all of the menu font sizes

00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:12.470
or the font size in the devices’ command-line
interface.

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:17.960
To make it easier to see in the videos I set
the font sizes fairly large, but feel free

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:20.830
to set whatever size you prefer.

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:23.490
You can also change the font colors.

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:28.330
For example, if you want to feel like you’re
in the Matrix, change the Router IOS Text

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:33.070
to green, and the Router IOS Background to
black.

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:35.650
Then hit apply and exit.

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:39.680
Then click on the Internet router and go to
the CLI tab.

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:42.129
And hey, now you’re officially a hacker.

00:07:42.129 --> 00:07:46.350
CLI stands for Command-Line Interface, by
the way.

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:50.360
This is how we are going to be configuring
routers and switches in the course.

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:56.039
Anyway, I’ll exit from here and let’s
actually do this first lab, which involves

00:07:56.039 --> 00:08:03.620
re-creating the network displayed at 16:40
of the Day 1 lecture video about network devices.

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:06.039
Here’s that network.

00:08:06.039 --> 00:08:08.319
In the middle there is the Internet.

00:08:08.319 --> 00:08:12.660
In this lab I’m just using a router to represent
the Internet.

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:19.350
Then there is the New York Branch on the left
with some PCs, a switch, a router, and a firewall.

00:08:19.350 --> 00:08:24.919
And in the Tokyo branch there are two servers,
a switch, a firewall, and a router.

00:08:24.919 --> 00:08:29.560
Also somewhere over the Internet there is
an attacker.

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:32.339
Okay so let’s re-create that network.

00:08:32.339 --> 00:08:37.830
For the routers, the instructions say to use
Cisco 2911 routers, the same kind of router

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:40.149
I used for The Internet.

00:08:40.149 --> 00:08:45.910
To place a device in Packet Tracer go to the
bottom left here and click on this icon for

00:08:45.910 --> 00:08:49.290
network devices, and then routers.

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:55.399
Then you can see a selection of router models,
let’s select the 2911 and place two of them

00:08:55.399 --> 00:08:57.200
in the network.

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:02.100
This is what a Cisco ISR 2911 router looks
like, by the way.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:08.540
‘ISR’ is a line of Cisco routers, and
2911 is a particular model in that line.

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:15.160
Okay, next let’s go to the switches menu
here and place two 2960 switches in the network.

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:20.269
Here’s a photo of a Cisco Catalyst 2960
switch, by the way.

00:09:20.269 --> 00:09:26.880
Catalyst is the name of a line of Cisco switch
models, and 2960 is one model within that

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:28.080
line.

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:33.750
Okay, next we’ll place the two firewalls
by going to the firewall menu and placing

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:37.060
two 5505 firewalls.

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:42.310
Note that, in the network diagram in the Day
1 lecture video, the New York branch firewall

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:47.399
is between the router and the Internet, and
the Tokyo branch firewall is between the router

00:09:47.399 --> 00:09:48.800
and the switch.

00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:54.440
Depending on the network design, you might
find the firewall placed in either position.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:58.990
This is a photo of a Cisco ASA 5505 firewall.

00:09:58.990 --> 00:10:06.660
ASA is a series of firewalls made by Cisco,
and 5505 is a particular model within the

00:10:06.660 --> 00:10:09.160
ASA line.

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:14.040
Okay now let’s place the end devices like
the PCs and servers.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:21.060
Go to the ‘end devices’ menu, and here
in the end devices tab we can find PCs, servers,

00:10:21.060 --> 00:10:22.060
etc.

00:10:22.060 --> 00:10:28.570
So, place two PCs in the New York branch,
and two servers in the Tokyo Branch.

00:10:28.570 --> 00:10:33.950
Then, to represent the attacker in the diagram
place a laptop.

00:10:33.950 --> 00:10:37.529
Okay, now all of the devices are placed.

00:10:37.529 --> 00:10:41.760
This isn’t in the lab instructions, but
let’s rename them to match the diagram in

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:43.920
the lecture video.

00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:47.230
To rename a device, just click on the device
name.

00:10:47.230 --> 00:10:58.410
PC1 already has the correct name, so I’ll
start on PC2...then SW1...then R1...then FW1...then

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:09.959
R2...then FW2...then SW2...then SRV1...then
SRV2...and finally the attacker.

00:11:09.959 --> 00:11:14.779
Okay, now we’ve placed and named all of
the devices.

00:11:14.779 --> 00:11:19.950
To connect devices in packet tracer, click
on this lightning bolt icon here.

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:25.279
Now, in the next video of the course we will
study different types of cables used to connect

00:11:25.279 --> 00:11:27.519
devices together in a network.

00:11:27.519 --> 00:11:32.970
So, for this video we will just let packet
tracer pick the cables for us, by clicking

00:11:32.970 --> 00:11:37.260
this lightning bolt which says ‘automatically
choose connection type’.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:43.570
So, I’ll click on that, click on PC1, and
then click on SW1.

00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:46.060
And now they are connected.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:48.930
Then I’ll do the same to connect PC2 to
SW1.

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:52.589
Now, here’s a trick to speed things up.

00:11:52.589 --> 00:11:57.540
Hold down the control key on your keyboard
and click on the lightning bolt.

00:11:57.540 --> 00:12:00.170
Then I’ll connect SW1 to R1.

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:04.570
But notice after connecting them, I don’t
have to click the lightning bolt again, it

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:08.130
is still selected because I held down control
while clicking it.

00:12:08.130 --> 00:12:17.810
So, I’ll connect R1 to FW1, FW1 to the Internet,
The Internet to R2, R2 to FW2, FW2 to SW2,

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:26.610
SW2 to SRV1, SW2 to SRV2, and finally the
attacker to the Internet.

00:12:26.610 --> 00:12:30.529
Now they’re all connected so I’ll click
cancel here, since I don’t need to do any

00:12:30.529 --> 00:12:31.740
more connections.

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:35.230
Okay, we’re done with the lab instructions.

00:12:35.230 --> 00:12:41.170
We have successfully recreated the network
diagram as shown in the lecture videos.

00:12:41.170 --> 00:12:45.579
Most days of the course will include a packet
tracer lab so you can practice configuring

00:12:45.579 --> 00:12:48.000
Cisco routers and switches.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:53.279
Ideally, you should try to complete the lab
on your own in packet tracer after watching

00:12:53.279 --> 00:12:55.579
the lecture video.

00:12:55.579 --> 00:12:59.529
Then you can check my lab video after to confirm
your solutions.

00:12:59.529 --> 00:13:04.089
However, if you’re having trouble doing
the practice labs on your own, feel free to

00:13:04.089 --> 00:13:07.880
watch each lab video before actually trying
the lab in packet tracer.

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:09.980
That’s not a problem.

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:14.800
The important thing is that you get hands-on
practice with Cisco routers and switches to

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:19.649
deepen your understanding of the concepts
we cover in the course, and also to prepare

00:13:19.649 --> 00:13:20.850
for the exam.

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:22.870
Okay, that’s all for this video.

00:13:22.870 --> 00:13:27.360
I hope it was helpful, thanks for watching.

